    "summary": "The Weimar Republic was the democratic government of Germany established after the November 1918 revolution that ended [[event:110|World War I]] and forced Kaiser Wilhelm II to abdicate. Named for the city where its constitution was drafted, the republic governed Germany from 1919 until 1933 when Adolf Hitler's seizure of power effectively ended it. The Weimar Republic is primarily studied as a fragile democratic experiment that ultimately failed, but it also represents a period of significant cultural creativity and political experimentation.\n\nThe republic faced severe challenges from its inception. The [[event:2644|Treaty of Versailles]] imposed humiliating peace terms that the new government was forced to accept, associating it with national shame in the minds of many Germans. Hyperinflation in 1923 wiped out the savings of the middle class, while the [[event:2650|Great Depression]] after 1929 created mass unemployment that radicalized the electorate. The republic was attacked simultaneously from the radical left, which sought a Soviet-style revolution, and from the nationalist right, which rejected democratic politics as un-German. Constitutional weaknesses, including emergency powers provisions and proportional representation that fragmented the party system, made stable governance difficult.\n\nWeimar's cultural legacy is significant: Berlin in particular became a center of artistic modernism, intellectual life, and social experimentation, producing influential work in cinema, visual art, literature, and philosophy. This flowering was destroyed by the Nazi seizure of power in 1933, which drove many of Germany's greatest cultural and intellectual figures into exile.",
